Enzymes, antibodies, or DNA strands are examples of biological elements that biological nanosensors include into their structure (Khanna, 2021). The sensor can identify and react to certain biological or chemical entities thanks to the specificity these components give. Applications needing high selectivity, such identifying certain viruses or biomolecules, benefit greatly from this kind of nanosensor. Biological nanosensors are useful for both environmental monitoring and medical diagnostics, where they may be designed to recognize specific contaminants or disorders (Javaid et al., 2021). Fig. 2
                         represents the overview of Nanosensors and their revolutionary Applications (Table 2
                        ).
